File Name Examples (SFTP, GCS, Azure)

Based on the values configured for the fields of your activation target (SFTP, GCS, Azure), here are some examples of file names.

FILE NAME	DESCRIPTION
TeenagersInNewyork_EmailCampaign_2023-07-30-17-55-45-216_00000.csv	

Non-compressed / Non-encrypted CSV file with date/time suffix. This file name is predetermined based on the segment name and activation name.

TeenagersInNewyork - Segment name
EmailCampaign - Activation name
2023-07-30-17-55-45-216 - Date/time suffix along with milliseconds that refer to the segment publish time
00000 - Part number. If multiple files are generated when the file size hits its maximum, the number of part files (00000, 00001, 00002, and so on) depends on the volume of activated data
.csv - File extension

TeenagersInNewyork_EmailCampaign_2023-07-30-17-55-45-216_00000.parquet.gz	Compressed / non-encrypted parquet file with date/time suffix. The gz refers to the compressed file
TeenagersInNewyork_EmailCampaign_2023-07-30-17-55-45-216_00000.json.bz2.pgp	Compressed / PGP encrypted JSON file with date/time suffix in milliseconds. The bz2 refers to the compressed file, and the pgp refers to the encrypted file. PGP encryption is applicable only for SFTP activation target.
WinterOffersForMobileAudience_2023-07-30-17-55-45_00000.json	A custom file name. All activations to the activation target contain the same custom file name with a different date/time suffix based on the segment publish time

For each activation and the activation payload (which contains the data exported from Data Cloud), a segment metadata JSON file is generated. The file contains the segment ID and name, record count, publish refresh type, and the attribute names with the data type of each activated attribute.

An example of a segment metadata JSON file name: TeenagersInNewyork_EmailCampaign_2023-07-30-17-55-45-216_segment_metadata.json

The segment metadata JSON file is in the same directory where the data files are placed.
